The study employed single-cell RNA sequencing to analyze the transcriptomic landscape of the human retinal pigment epithelium (RPE) and choroid, particularly focusing on regions related to age-related macular degeneration (AMD). Two experiments were conducted using samples from seven human donor eyes. The first involved total RPE/choroid preparations to identify expression profiles of various RPE and choroidal cell populations. In the second experiment, endothelial cells were enriched via magnetic separation to explore their gene expression patterns, revealing distinct signatures for choriocapillaris, arterial, and venous endothelial cells. Notably, RGCC, a gene implicated in apoptosis and complement response, was found significantly upregulated in choriocapillaris endothelial cells from an AMD donor. The findings enhance understanding of choroidal vascular responses to complement activation and may provide insights into AMD pathogenesis, underlining the importance of these tissues in visual health and disease.
